Solution:
Let $r$ and $\theta$ be the polar coordinates of the point $(\cos x, \sin x).$  Then
\[\cos x + 2 \sin x = r \cos (\theta - \alpha),\]where $\alpha$ is the angle such that $\cos \alpha = \frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}$ and $\sin \alpha = \frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}.$

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

pair A, B, O, X, Y;

A = (1,0.5);
O = (0,0);
X = (1,0);
Y = (0,0.5);
B = (2/sqrt(5),1/sqrt(5));

draw((-0.2,0)--(2,0));
draw((0,-0.2)--(0,1.2));
draw(O--A,red,Arrow(6));
draw(O--B,blue,Arrow(6));
draw(A--B,dashed);

label("$\theta$", A + (0.15,-0.3));
label("$\alpha$", B + (0.2,-0.3));
label("$r \cos (\theta - \alpha)$", (A + B)/2, NE);
label("$r$", (O + A)/2, SE);

dot("$O$", O, SW);
dot("$A$", A, NE);
dot("$B$", B, NE);
[/asy]

Then
\begin{align*}
r &= \sqrt{\cos^2 x + \sin^2 x} = 1, \\
r \cos (\theta - \alpha) &= \cos x + 2 \sin x \le \sqrt{(\cos^2 x + \sin^2 x)(1^2 + 2^2)} = \sqrt{5}.
\end{align*}Equality occurs when $\cos x = \frac{2}{\sqrt{5}}$ and $\sin x = \frac{1}{\sqrt{5}}.$  Therefore, the maximum value is $\boxed{\sqrt{5}}.$

